subject: Removed hardcoded service paths in getBootProgress
commitMessage:
Removed hardcoded service paths in getBootProgress

Taking into account the comments given on one of my previous commits
I noticed that there were hardcoded service paths in other functions
in bmcweb. While waiting for a Bitbake to build I thought it would
be ideal to apply the mapper to these LOC.

Signed-off-by: Corey Hardesty <corey.hardesty@icloud.com>
Change-Id: I66b82f59a75eb2c84346d112681ae5ab4ac61f13

I suspect this should be using GetObject, because the old code verified that the path was /xyz/openbmc_project/state/host0.  I would expect this to do the same, to avoid cases where other paths get used accidentally.
so basically I'm only interested in retrieving the service?
If you're only retrieving one known path, you use GetObject.  If you're retrieving multiple paths, you use GetSubTree.
Done
Please use MapperGetObject, similar to what was here before (but using hte right command.

Sorry, I was using a downstream bmcweb to build my image so MapperGetObject was not implemented. I added it to the dbus_utility.hpp and have been trying to test it on Simics. 
Once Simis decides to boot I should have this tested.
Done
I think this already got fixed on master.  Please rebase and most of this should go away.
I rebased with master and this stuff was still there 😕

We are adding a mapper call here.. 
I thought Host State manager was one of the services it was okay to call directly..?
https://discord.com/channels/775381525260664832/981267481966571580/981282235191804044

After reading through the thread I guess in defense of the commit it would make sense to use mapper since the existence of the property 'BootProgress' may or may not exist in some systems, and mapper seems to be useful in those scenarios.
Ultimately, I made this commit because I had time one day and in another commit I made for bmcweb was instructed there to use mapper calls as supposed to hard-coding service paths for re-usability when in the future there may be more than one. 

However, the mapper call is not needed because this property is hosted in state-manager and can be grabbed easily with an asio dbus call. I was never explicitly told to do this, but I do see it's potential benefits(other than the listed concerns such as race conditions with the mapper calls themselves).

Discord is shedding light on why I'm running into sensor failures in the Jenkins build job.
